CONTACT;X-BEDEWORK-UID=00f1fcdb-0f068baf-010f-068baf83-00000004:None
CREATED:20250218T175039Z
DESCRIPTION:Long COVID\, also known as postacute sequelae of SARS-CoV-2 in
 fection (PASC)\, is a chronic condition characterized by long-term sympto
 ms that persist for months or even years after initial SARS-CoV-2 infecti
 on. Over 200 symptoms have been identified as being associated with Long 
 COVID\, affecting nearly every body system. Long COVID is known to manife
 st differently across individuals\, wax and wane over time\, and range fr
 om mild to incapacitating\, with profound effects on quality of life. Whi
 le recognition of Long COVID is growing among adults\, it is still woeful
 ly understudied in children. The rapid materialization of large-scale obs
 ervational data\, including the Researching COVID to Enhance Recovery (RE
 COVER) meta-cohort\, has generated enormous opportunity for novel discove
 ry that could lead to effective prevention strategies and improved outcom
 es for patients living with Long COVID. The statistical challenges inhere
 nt in effectively and appropriately leveraging these novel data resources
  are numerous. In this talk\, I will discuss my role as lead biostatistic
 ian of the Data Resource Core for RECOVER\, present our work developing a
  working definition for a new chronic disease\, and highlight the many st
 atistical challenges in the study of Long COVID. \n\n\nZoom webinar link:
  https://duke.zoom.us/j/95276961581?pwd=y8FxiY7yBCweJ5zJddxMOzh7qikHTh.1\
 n\nThis event is being cross-promoted by the NC BERD Consortium\, a colla
 boration of the CTSA-funded BERD cores at UNC-Chapel Hill\, Wake Forest U
 niversity School of Medicine\, and Duke University School of Medicine.
DURATION:PT1H
DTSTAMP:20260303T225212Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260311T160000
LAST-MODIFIED:20260303T225212Z
LOCATION;X-BEDEWORK-UID=2c918085-71ed832f-0172-098647fa-0000767f:Virtual
STATUS:CONFIRMED
